Chapter 2: Related Work

2.1 Meta‑Learning and Neural Architecture Search

Meta‑learning (Finn et al., 2017; Nichol et al., 2018) optimizes initial parameters for fast adaptation. NAS (Zoph & Le, 2017; Liu et al., 2019) searches over architectures, often using differentiable relaxations (DARTS). Both fields treat architecture search as a separate phase; recursion is not considered. Our work extends them by allowing continuous, recursive architectural updates interleaved with learning.

2.2 Contraction Theory in Machine Learning

Contraction theory (Lohmiller & Slotine, 1998) analyzes convergence of nonlinear systems via differential Lyapunov functions. Tsukamoto et al. (2021) provide a comprehensive tutorial and apply it to neural ODEs. We adopt their differential contraction framework, using the Fisher metric as the contraction metric $G(\psi)$.

2.3 Information Geometry of Neural Networks

Amari (1998) introduced the Fisher metric for neural networks. Karakida et al. (2019) studied the spectrum of the Fisher information matrix in wide networks. Our manifold builds on these ideas but adds architectural parameters as continuous variables via softmax gating, ensuring a fixed‑dimension parameter space.

2.4 Safe Recursive Self‑Improvement

Schmidhuber (2007) proposed Gödel machines, and Hutter (2005) AIXI. More recently, Wu et al. (2025) introduced the Statistical Gödel Machine, which uses e‑values to bound the risk of recursive modifications. Our work complements theirs by providing geometric stability conditions that can be monitored online, and we discuss how e‑values can be integrated to halt the process if instability is detected.

2.5 Riemannian Optimization

Boumal (2023) provides a modern treatment of optimization on manifolds, including descent lemmas and curvature bounds. We use these results as a foundation for our improvement theorem.

