Appendix A: Proof of Metric Equivalence (Lemma 3.2)

We restate Lemma 3.2:

Lemma 3.2 (Metric Equivalence on $\mathcal{K}$).
Let $\mathcal{K} \subset \mathcal{M}^\circ$ be a compact set on which the Fisher metric $g$ satisfies uniform bounds $\mu_{\min} I \le F(\psi) \le \mu_{\max} I$ for all $\psi \in \mathcal{K}$. Then for any $\psi_1,\psi_2 \in \mathcal{K}$,

> \sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2) \le d_g(\psi_1,\psi_2) \le \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2),
> \]  

where $d_g$ is the geodesic distance induced by $g$, and $d_E$ is the Euclidean distance in the ambient space $\mathbb{R}^{P+W}$.

Proof. Let $\gamma:[0,1]\to\mathcal{K}$ be any piecewise $C^1$ curve joining $\psi_1$ and $\psi_2$. Its length with respect to $g$ is

L_g(\gamma) = \int_0^1 \sqrt{\dot\gamma(t)^\top F(\gamma(t)) \dot\gamma(t)}\, dt.

From the eigenvalue bounds, for each $t$ we have

\sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, \|\dot\gamma(t)\| \le \sqrt{\dot\gamma(t)^\top F(\gamma(t)) \dot\gamma(t)} \le \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, \|\dot\gamma(t)\|.

Integrating gives

\sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, L_E(\gamma) \le L_g(\gamma) \le \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, L_E(\gamma),

where $L_E(\gamma)$ is the Euclidean length of $\gamma$.

Now, $d_g(\psi_1,\psi_2)$ is defined as the infimum of $L_g(\gamma)$ over all such curves, and $d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2)$ is the infimum of $L_E(\gamma)$ (in fact, the Euclidean infimum is attained by the straight line). Therefore,

d_g(\psi_1,\psi_2) \le \inf_\gamma \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, L_E(\gamma) = \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2).

For the lower bound, we use that for any curve $\gamma$,

\sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, L_E(\gamma) \le L_g(\gamma) \le \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, L_E(\gamma).

Taking infimum over $\gamma$ on the left and right yields

\sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, \inf_\gamma L_E(\gamma) \le \inf_\gamma L_g(\gamma) \le \sqrt{\mu_{\max}} \, \inf_\gamma L_E(\gamma).

But $\inf_\gamma L_E(\gamma) = d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2)$ (since the straight line achieves it), and $\inf_\gamma L_g(\gamma) = d_g(\psi_1,\psi_2)$. Hence

\sqrt{\mu_{\min}} \, d_E(\psi_1,\psi_2) \le d_g(\psi_1,\psi_2).

∎

This proof uses only the pointwise quadratic form bounds and the definition of geodesic distance as an infimum over lengths; no geodesic completeness or smoothness of the metric beyond continuity is required.

