Appendix E: TLA⁺ Specification and Dafny Code

E.1 TLA⁺ Specification

We provide a high‑level TLA⁺ specification of the RecursNet algorithm. The state consists of theta, alpha, and a step counter. The transition relation models one recursion step, including projection and the contraction check. We use Euclidean distance as proxy.

```tla
------------------------ MODULE RecursNet ------------------------
EXTENDS Naturals, Reals, Sequences

CONSTANTS R, C, k_E, delta

VARIABLES theta, alpha, step

vars == <<theta, alpha, step>>

Init == /\ theta \in [ -R, R ]^P
        /\ alpha \in [delta, 1-delta]^W  /\ Sum(alpha) = 1
        /\ step = 0

Next == \E dtheta, dalpha \in Real^P x Real^W :
          /\ LET theta1 = theta - eta_theta * grad_theta(theta, alpha)
                 alpha1 = alpha - eta_alpha * grad_alpha(theta1, alpha)
             IN
             /\ theta' = ProjectBall(theta1, R)
             /\ alpha' = ProjectSimplex(alpha1, delta)
             /\ step' = step + 1
             /\ DistanceEuclidean(<<theta', alpha'>>, <<theta, alpha>>) <= k_E * DistanceEuclidean(<<theta, alpha>>, <<theta_prev, alpha_prev>>)

Spec == Init /\ [][Next]_vars

Invariant == /\ theta \in [ -R, R ]^P
             /\ alpha \in [delta, 1-delta]^W /\ Sum(alpha) = 1
========================================================================
```

The functions grad_theta, grad_alpha, ProjectBall, ProjectSimplex, and DistanceEuclidean are defined in the standard TLA⁺ real number library. The constant k_E is chosen as $k_{\text{desired}} \cdot (c_{\min}/c_{\max})$ as explained in Section 4.3.

We use the TLC model checker to verify that the invariant holds for all reachable states and that the distance contraction condition is maintained.

E.2 Dafny Code

We implement a simplified version of RecursNet in Dafny, focusing on proving the invariance of bounds and the contraction property under the Euclidean metric. We assume the existence of constants mu_min, mu_max and the equivalence lemma.

```dafny
lemma MetricEquivalence(x: seq<real>, y: seq<real>)
    requires |x| == |y| == N
    ensures mu_min * EuclideanDistance(x, y) <= FisherDistance(x, y) <= mu_max * EuclideanDistance(x, y)
{ ... }

method RecursNetStep(theta: array<real>, alpha: array<real>, eta_theta: real, eta_alpha: real, k_E: real)
    requires theta.Length == P && alpha.Length == W
    requires forall i :: -R <= theta[i] <= R
    requires forall i :: delta <= alpha[i] <= 1-delta && Sum(alpha) == 1.0
    requires k_E > 0.0
    modifies theta, alpha
    ensures forall i :: -R <= theta[i] <= R
    ensures forall i :: delta <= alpha[i] <= 1-delta && Sum(alpha) == 1.0
    ensures EuclideanDistance(new_theta+new_alpha, old_theta+old_alpha) <= k_E * EuclideanDistance(old_theta+old_alpha, prev_theta+prev_alpha)
{
    var grad_theta := ComputeGradTheta(theta, alpha);
    var theta1 := Subtract(theta, Scale(grad_theta, eta_theta));
    ProjectBall(theta1, R, theta);  // modifies theta to projected value

    var grad_alpha := ComputeGradAlpha(theta, alpha);
    var alpha1 := Subtract(alpha, Scale(grad_alpha, eta_alpha));
    ProjectSimplex(alpha1, delta, alpha); // modifies alpha

    // Contract condition is ensured by calling context with appropriate k_E
}
```

The proof obligations are discharged using Dafny's verification conditions, assuming appropriate lemmas about the projection functions and the arithmetic.

